</th>
</tr>
<tr pageId="0" pageNumber="213">
<td colspan="3" pageId="0" pageNumber="213" rowspan="1">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="213">Both sexes</emphasis>
</td>
</tr>
<tr pageId="0" pageNumber="213">
<td colspan="1" pageId="0" pageNumber="213" rowspan="1">Transverse anterior concavity of scutellum</td>
<td colspan="1" pageId="0" pageNumber="213" rowspan="1">ribs very short, poorly distinguishable</td>
<td colspan="1" pageId="0" pageNumber="213" rowspan="1">
with clearly visible ribs (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Hoplisoides gazagnairei (Handlirsch) from Tunisia [FSCV] (A-C), and H. distinguendus (Yasumatsu) from Buryatia, Russia [FSCV] (D-F), males: A, D clypeus, frontolateral view B, E scutellum, metanotum and propodeum, posterolateral view C, F metasoma, ventral view." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.79.56839.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/469676" pageId="0" pageNumber="213">5E</figureCitation>
)
</td>
</tr>
<tr pageId="0" pageNumber="213">
<td colspan="1" pageId="0" pageNumber="213" rowspan="1">Form of acetabular carina and omaulus</td>
<td colspan="1" pageId="0" pageNumber="213" rowspan="1">
acetabular carina reaching omaulus, omaulus-sternaulus angularly very sharp curved (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Hoplisoides gazagnairei (Handlirsch) from Tunisia [FSCV] (A-C), and H. distinguendus (Yasumatsu) from Buryatia, Russia [FSCV] (D-F), males: A, D clypeus, frontolateral view B, E scutellum, metanotum and propodeum, posterolateral view C, F metasoma, ventral view." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.79.56839.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/469676" pageId="0" pageNumber="213">5C</figureCitation>
)
</td>
<td colspan="1" pageId="0" pageNumber="213" rowspan="1">
acetabular carina far from reaching omaulus, omaulus-sternaulus opposite end of acetabular carina not or slightly curved (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Hoplisoides gazagnairei (Handlirsch) from Tunisia [FSCV] (A-C), and H. distinguendus (Yasumatsu) from Buryatia, Russia [FSCV] (D-F), males: A, D clypeus, frontolateral view B, E scutellum, metanotum and propodeum, posterolateral view C, F metasoma, ventral view." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.79.56839.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/469676" pageId="0" pageNumber="213">5F</figureCitation>
)
</td>
</tr>
<tr pageId="0" pageNumber="213">
<td colspan="1" pageId="0" pageNumber="213" rowspan="1">Propodeum</td>
<td colspan="1" pageId="0" pageNumber="213" rowspan="1">
dorsolaterally with coarse punctation and rugose sculpture; gibbous; edges of metapostnotum poorly visible (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Hoplisoides gazagnairei (Handlirsch) from Tunisia [FSCV] (A-C), and H. distinguendus (Yasumatsu) from Buryatia, Russia [FSCV] (D-F), males: A, D clypeus, frontolateral view B, E scutellum, metanotum and propodeum, posterolateral view C, F metasoma, ventral view." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.79.56839.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/469676" pageId="0" pageNumber="213">5B</figureCitation>
)
</td>
<td colspan="1" pageId="0" pageNumber="213" rowspan="1">
dorsolaterally smooth, with space not large punctation; uniformly convex; metapostnotum clearly separated (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Hoplisoides gazagnairei (Handlirsch) from Tunisia [FSCV] (A-C), and H. distinguendus (Yasumatsu) from Buryatia, Russia [FSCV] (D-F), males: A, D clypeus, frontolateral view B, E scutellum, metanotum and propodeum, posterolateral view C, F metasoma, ventral view." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.79.56839.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/469676" pageId="0" pageNumber="213">5E</figureCitation>
)
</td>
</tr>
<tr pageId="0" pageNumber="213">
<td colspan="3" pageId="0" pageNumber="213" rowspan="1">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="213">Males</emphasis>
</td>
</tr>
<tr pageId="0" pageNumber="213">
<td colspan="1" pageId="0" pageNumber="213" rowspan="1">Apicoposterior spine on male hind tarsomeres 1-3</td>
<td colspan="1" pageId="0" pageNumber="213" rowspan="1">as long as apicoanterior spine</td>
<td colspan="1" pageId="0" pageNumber="213" rowspan="1">
2-3 times longer than apicoanterior spine (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Hoplisoides gazagnairei (Handlirsch) from Tunisia [FSCV] (A-B), and H. distinguendus (Yasumatsu) from Buryatia, Russia [FSCV] (C-F), males: A, C antenna, dorsal view B, D foretarsus, dorsal view E midtarsus, dorsal view F hindtarsus, dorsal view." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.79.56839.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/469677" pageId="0" pageNumber="213">6F</figureCitation>
)
</td>
</tr>
<tr pageId="0" pageNumber="213">
<td colspan="1" pageId="0" pageNumber="213" rowspan="1">Clypeus</td>
<td colspan="1" pageId="0" pageNumber="213" rowspan="1">
apical margin with median weak bilobate protrusion; lateral setae not combined into brush (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Hoplisoides gazagnairei (Handlirsch) from Tunisia [FSCV] (A-C), and H. distinguendus (Yasumatsu) from Buryatia, Russia [FSCV] (D-F), males: A, D clypeus, frontolateral view B, E scutellum, metanotum and propodeum, posterolateral view C, F metasoma, ventral view." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.79.56839.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/469676" pageId="0" pageNumber="213">5A</figureCitation>
)
</td>
<td colspan="1" pageId="0" pageNumber="213" rowspan="1">
apical margin without median protrusion, with simple wide excision; lateral setae combined into thin brush (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Hoplisoides gazagnairei (Handlirsch) from Tunisia [FSCV] (A-C), and H. distinguendus (Yasumatsu) from Buryatia, Russia [FSCV] (D-F), males: A, D clypeus, frontolateral view B, E scutellum, metanotum and propodeum, posterolateral view C, F metasoma, ventral view." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.79.56839.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/469676" pageId="0" pageNumber="213">5D</figureCitation>
)
</td>
</tr>
<tr pageId="0" pageNumber="213">
<td colspan="1" pageId="0" pageNumber="213" rowspan="1">Antenna</td>
<td colspan="1" pageId="0" pageNumber="213" rowspan="1">
flagellomeres shorter, F10-F11 visibly transverse, F12 ratio length to width near 1.4 (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Hoplisoides gazagnairei (Handlirsch) from Tunisia [FSCV] (A-B), and H. distinguendus (Yasumatsu) from Buryatia, Russia [FSCV] (C-F), males: A, C antenna, dorsal view B, D foretarsus, dorsal view E midtarsus, dorsal view F hindtarsus, dorsal view." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.79.56839.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/469677" pageId="0" pageNumber="213">6A</figureCitation>
)
</td>
<td colspan="1" pageId="0" pageNumber="213" rowspan="1">
flagellomeres longer, F10 cubelike, F11 longer whan wide, F12 ratio length to width near 1.9 (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Hoplisoides gazagnairei (Handlirsch) from Tunisia [FSCV] (A-B), and H. distinguendus (Yasumatsu) from Buryatia, Russia [FSCV] (C-F), males: A, C antenna, dorsal view B, D foretarsus, dorsal view E midtarsus, dorsal view F hindtarsus, dorsal view." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.79.56839.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/469677" pageId="0" pageNumber="213">6C</figureCitation>
)
</td>
</tr>
<tr pageId="0" pageNumber="213">
<td colspan="1" pageId="0" pageNumber="213" rowspan="1">Foretarsomeres 2-4</td>
<td colspan="1" pageId="0" pageNumber="213" rowspan="1">
transverse (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Hoplisoides gazagnairei (Handlirsch) from Tunisia [FSCV] (A-B), and H. distinguendus (Yasumatsu) from Buryatia, Russia [FSCV] (C-F), males: A, C antenna, dorsal view B, D foretarsus, dorsal view E midtarsus, dorsal view F hindtarsus, dorsal view." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.79.56839.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/469677" pageId="0" pageNumber="213">6B</figureCitation>
)
</td>
<td colspan="1" pageId="0" pageNumber="213" rowspan="1">
strongly transverse (Fig. 
